Germany postpones launch of new warship
The latest frigate of the German fleet had to be put into operation in 2014 to replace the outdated Cold War-era battleships, but this would not happen until next year due to faulty systems and arbitrarily growing cost, local media reported.
The launch of the Rheinland-Pfalz brand-leading new frigates from the Baden-Wuerttemberg class was postponed until the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit newspaper, which quoted an army spokesman as saying.
The vessel had to join the naval forces in 2014, but the problems that arose after its delivery affected the fate of the ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class, commissioned by the fleet in 2007, will replace the outdated Bremen-class frigates.
It is understandable that they will have powerful weapons, a set of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stealth technologies, e.g. reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signals.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods – the latest frigates should be able to be used for up to two years before returning to the port of residence.
However, continuous delays mean that vanguard warships – which are said to allow Germany to demonstrate force across the ocean – will be old when they enter into operation, Die Zeit said.
The F125 became headlines last year, when the German fleet officially refused to release the vessel into operation and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the fleet has returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but German media quoted a number of significant “software and hardware defects” that make the warship unusable if sent on a combat mission.
Software disadvantages are particularly important, as the Baden-Wuerttemberg class vessels will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors – only half of the crew of the older Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, it turned out that the ship is significantly overloaded, which reduces its effectiveness and limits the possibility of the naval forces to add future upgrades.
It is believed that the 7,000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz is twice as heavy as the ships of a similar class used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to the faulty hardware, the cost of the entire project – including training the crew – also becomes a problem.
It is believed to have reached 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion) from the initial 2.2 billion euros.
The problems with the latest frigates have become particularly important in light of recent warnings that the German naval forces are shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the defense committee of the German parliament, admitted that the fleet was actually “exhausted from ships capable of carrying out missions”.
