National Trust Tracks Secret Life of Bats
A new study carried out at an estate in the Scottish mountains aims to determine how bats use the landscape when hunting.
Hopes are that the discoveries will shed new light on the behavior of unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation actions.
The study by scientists from Scotland’s National Trust will follow the common bats, as well as the brown arrow water nights at Inverewe Gardens in Western Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in key places in the property to track the activities of the bats during the season.
NHS employees and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using manual detectors.
The expert sound analysis of all records will determine the frequency of the call sounds of the bats, as well as what types they issue.
Then a map of the habitat and a report will be drawn up to create a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Duar, Nature Conservation Advisor for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used of any kind.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, e.g. creating meadows, as well as the best way to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
The populations of bats in Scotland and Britain have generally declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction activities that affect their refuges and lead to loss of habitats.
There may be a risk to populations from wind turbines and lighting, aircraft and some chemical processing of building materials, as well as domestic cat attacks.
In fact, the blind are not blind.
However, because of their hunting habits at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation technique to detect insects and obstacles to their flight trajectory.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of great importance and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes the bats very seriously.
The Trust has trained experts who conduct regular research, shelter inspections and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization even created the first in Scotland and the only special bat reserve in the Threee estate in the Dumfries and Galaway area, which is home to eight of the ten species of bats in Scotland.
The owner of the estate, David Thompson, said it was an ideal territory for them.
“Here, in Threeve, we have great terrain for the bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, many adult trees and a finished suitable habitat.
But there are many more things about bats that are not known, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive.
He stressed that it is important to check for the presence of bats before real estate maintenance activities are carried out, as it is possible that the involuntary destruction of one asylum will kill up to 400 female and young bats, as well as destroy the entire local population.
The bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disrupt or destroy their refuges.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish officer in the Trust for the Protection of the Bats, encouraged society to help.
She said, “I still have a lot to learn about our bats and many of our animal species, because we just don’t know what’s going on with their populations.”
